WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.360
Hi everyone, sorry, my name is Allison Hill. I'm a data scientist and professional educator

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:18.879
at RStudio. Welcome to Learning and Using with R. Our first speaker is Gina Reynolds.

00:00:18.879 --> 00:00:30.200
Hey, good afternoon. Yes, my name is Gina Reynolds, and I'm here to talk to you today

00:00:30.200 --> 00:00:36.040
about flipbooks and a new package for creating them called Flipbook R. Just a little bit

00:00:36.040 --> 00:00:43.799
about me. I teach at the University of Denver in the Corvell School of International Studies,

00:00:43.799 --> 00:00:52.080
and I co-organize Denver R-Ladies. I tweet at Ava Mae Ray. I also write code on GitHub.

00:00:52.080 --> 00:01:00.720
I'm avamaeray there, too. And I used to do quite a fair amount of blogging on Netlify,

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:10.120
but I've been recently writing a lot more flipbooks. So just as a traditional flipbook

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:17.360
allows you to watch the evolution of a scene, our new code flipbooks allow you to watch

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:27.879
the evolution of a code pipeline. So formally, flipbooks present code and output side-by-side

00:01:27.879 --> 00:01:33.279
and step-by-step, and they deliver to you something that's like a stop-action movie

00:01:33.279 --> 00:01:42.400
based on looking over the shoulder of somebody that's actually building up a coding pipeline

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:49.199
and taking snapshots at appropriate moments, like they're checking their code, checking

00:01:49.199 --> 00:01:55.599
their work along the way and intermediate outputs. So I think to understand where we

00:01:55.599 --> 00:02:01.919
are with the project right now, it might be useful to look back in time to look at the

00:02:01.919 --> 00:02:09.039
origins of this project. And I'd say that in 2018, we were in the era of the proto-flipbook.

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:15.759
So Garrick, Aidan, Bui, and I and Emi Tanaka were all interacting with this idea of presenting

00:02:15.759 --> 00:02:23.679
code and output side-by-side and building it up incrementally. But at this time, the

00:02:23.679 --> 00:02:30.080
project that the projects that we were building were very handcrafted and artisanal. So we

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:39.919
were all crafting each slide that composed each mini-flipbook one-by-one, using a lot

00:02:39.919 --> 00:02:48.679
of copying and pasting. But I was excited to find these like-minded people, and so I

00:02:48.679 --> 00:02:53.679
approached them. They seemed to know a lot about the tool that we were building with

00:02:53.679 --> 00:03:03.600
Sharingan, and I asked them, do you want to build flipbooks together? We were all circling

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:10.000
around this idea. We thought the flipbooks could really deliver great experience to users,

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:17.759
deliver them a lot of insights about what's going on in a code pipeline. But to really

00:03:17.839 --> 00:03:23.679
reach flipbooks' full potential, we realized that we had to move away from this copy-paste

00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:29.759
modality. We had to move to something that unburdened the creator of flipbooks.

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:38.399
So we moved to automation. So now we're automatically parsing a block of input code

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:45.839
and automatically reconstructing code into partial builds, and then automatically delivering

00:03:46.639 --> 00:03:49.119
these partial builds onto a presentation platform.

00:03:51.520 --> 00:04:01.679
2019 was a year of exploration and refinement. We were interested in how we could use this

00:04:01.679 --> 00:04:08.880
new tool, different modalities to use it, using other people's code, breaking the flipbook

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:16.320
building code that we had developed. And in 2020, you can build a flipbook in five minutes

00:04:17.200 --> 00:04:24.239
with flipbook R, which is a development package on GitHub, using Sharingan as well.

00:04:26.239 --> 00:04:30.079
So we're going to do just that. We're going to build a flipbook in five minutes.

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:36.559
But first, a little bit of background. We're going to use ggplot2 in the demo,

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:45.760
but we're going to use a dialect of ggplot2 called slow ggplot. And slow ggplot2 is literally only

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:56.559
the wonderful ggplot2. So everything that we're going to be doing is native to ggplot2 and fully

00:04:56.559 --> 00:05:05.679
supported. It embraces incrementalism and feedback. So for every decision that you make, you're going

00:05:05.679 --> 00:05:14.799
to want, when possible, to have one ggplot statement. So you may be familiar with more

00:05:14.799 --> 00:05:23.920
this way of going about creating a ggplot, where you have a statement where your data is defined

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:31.119
and your aesthetic mapping. And then you say what geometric object you want to take on those

00:05:31.119 --> 00:05:41.679
aesthetics. And then say what labels you want. Contrasting this with slow ggplot, we start with

00:05:41.679 --> 00:05:50.880
data. Pipe that into a ggplot statement. Move to declare our X position aesthetic,

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:58.399
our Y position aesthetic, our geometric object. And then we can move to non-required aesthetics.

00:05:59.359 --> 00:06:06.640
And the label statements will make each of these decisions get their own ggplot statement.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:15.440
So the behavior that we're going after then will look like this. We've got our code on the one

00:06:15.519 --> 00:06:26.959
side and output on the other. Okay. So let's begin our live demo.

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:39.920
So delivered to you with a package is a template. So we can open that up by going to our markdown.

00:06:40.720 --> 00:06:45.119
And then from template, you'll grab a minimal flip book.

00:06:51.359 --> 00:06:57.119
And we're going to keep the YAML. And basically this will walk you through

00:06:58.959 --> 00:07:02.559
a lot of modalities that I'm going to talk you through earlier. So I'm going to just delete

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:11.119
most of the contents. And just keep the last code chunk, which is CSS. This is going to allow

00:07:11.119 --> 00:07:18.799
you to adjust the code font size pretty easily. Okay. And then I'm going to include a code chunk.

00:07:18.799 --> 00:07:31.040
We're going to use the tidyverse. And of course flip book R.

00:07:36.959 --> 00:07:47.440
Then I'm going to add a slide break. Three minus signs. No space. And we're going to start building

00:07:47.440 --> 00:07:55.679
our code pipeline. So I'm going to just use the cars dataset. Pipe that to ggplot.

00:07:57.920 --> 00:07:59.519
And we can check our code as we go.

00:08:03.679 --> 00:08:09.200
Add the aesthetic mapping. I'll have X represent speed.

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:26.160
And Y represent distance. And then add my geometric object.

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:44.799
And let's just do some multiple mapping for fun. We'll have color also represent speed.

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:54.400
Okay. So this is our source code chunk. And we don't actually want it to appear

00:08:55.119 --> 00:09:01.280
in the flip book. So we're going to set the code chunk option include to false.

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:08.719
And then we're going to refer to this code chunk with a name. I'm going to call it cars.

00:09:08.719 --> 00:09:33.599
And then we'll use the flip book function chunk reveal to reveal this coding pipeline.

00:09:34.559 --> 00:09:42.640
So the first argument here is the chunk name. That's cars. And we're all set to build our

00:09:42.640 --> 00:10:00.479
flip book. So I'm going to hit knit here in R studio. Save this as the flip book.

00:10:01.039 --> 00:10:10.479
And you can see that the build is happening. And you've created your first flip book.

00:10:12.799 --> 00:10:22.640
So what's going on is I'm using actually the auto mode of display. So what's being looked for

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:28.880
is balanced parentheses. And these are good places to take breaks along this coding pipeline.

00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:38.159
But you can also use the argument break type and set that to user.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:44.799
And with a special comment break in capital letters.

00:10:45.359 --> 00:10:50.719
You define where you want breaks along this pipeline. So let's just have a quick look at that.

00:11:01.119 --> 00:11:10.719
So two break points. Okay. So I'm going to go ahead and create a new break point.

00:11:11.119 --> 00:11:18.960
Two break points. Okay. So I'm going to present to you a few more modalities that you can use.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:27.760
An additional one is setting the break type to nonsequential. So this could be used in a

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:34.000
context where you want kind of this behavior for something to appear within your pipeline.

00:11:34.799 --> 00:11:41.599
But not right away. So here I would use that nonsequential setting and then set the break

00:11:41.599 --> 00:11:50.559
to here break and then the number two and then break three here. We can also set the break type

00:11:50.559 --> 00:11:59.599
to integer. And you might think of this as like entering the multiverse where you want code to be

00:11:59.599 --> 00:12:04.719
revealed multiple times just the same code. And this would be appropriate in a setting where

00:12:04.719 --> 00:12:10.719
you're doing some sampling. Taking a random sample. So here I'm sampling with replacement.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:19.280
Sample fraction. Replace equals true. We have these multiple realizations of the same code.

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:28.000
You can also set the argument display type. So the default is to display both the

00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:37.119
code and the output side by side. But you might want to display just the output. So maybe in a

00:12:37.119 --> 00:12:43.760
more traditional setting, in a presentation setting where you just want to slowly present

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:51.919
each component of a plot. You can also set display type to code. Just display the code.

00:12:52.719 --> 00:12:58.000
Maybe with students thinking about what their expectations are as you build up a plot.

00:12:59.359 --> 00:13:06.159
You can also tell longer stories with lip booking. So you might use a source code chunk

00:13:07.119 --> 00:13:13.679
and do some wrangling steps and then create an object within that code chunk and then

00:13:14.479 --> 00:13:17.280
have another source code chunk where you're doing some plotting.

00:13:18.159 --> 00:13:23.520
So that would look something like this. I created cars mod. And then working from there,

00:13:24.159 --> 00:13:33.599
I pipe into a plot. So you noticed that I used right assignment here. And you might be asking

00:13:33.599 --> 00:13:40.320
yourself, well, can I use left assignment? And flip booking allows for this too. And you just

00:13:40.719 --> 00:13:48.640
set the parameter left assigned to true. And what we do then is track the first object that

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:53.440
you create in your code chunk and print it at the bottom of the flip book.

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:06.239
And you can use flip booking beyond the tidyverse as well. For example, with this modality where

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:12.799
For example, with this modality where you kind of chain by overriding an object.

00:14:14.239 --> 00:14:16.880
So here you would set left assignment to true again.

00:14:19.919 --> 00:14:24.000
And you can also use brackets and logical indexing

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:27.919
by using this dot bracket syntax with the McGridder pipe.

00:14:28.880 --> 00:14:34.000
That would look something like this. And you can use flip booking with base R plotting too.

00:14:36.559 --> 00:14:42.960
Okay. So we've shown you that you can build a flip book pretty easily. But it does take

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:46.719
a little bit more effort. So you may be asking yourself, is it worth it?

00:14:49.200 --> 00:14:54.640
And I would argue that it delivers a lot of insights to newcomers when they see a long

00:14:54.719 --> 00:14:59.119
pipeline of code. I think that maybe the message is something like this.

00:15:01.679 --> 00:15:10.640
And even for more seasoned practitioners, I would say that an unfamiliar code within a long pipeline,

00:15:11.520 --> 00:15:17.679
it may be possible for them to infer what must be going on with that code. But I do think that

00:15:17.679 --> 00:15:24.559
this might require a lot of mental gymnastics. So I would say that you can use flip booking

00:15:25.440 --> 00:15:31.520
as a way to do that. But this is a very simple way to build a pipeline.

00:15:31.520 --> 00:15:37.119
And it's a lot more complicated than that. So, what does flipping do for us, though?

00:15:37.119 --> 00:15:39.760
Right? So, we're showing all these intermediary steps.

00:15:41.280 --> 00:15:45.119
But we could show them by infinitely scrolling through the steps.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:54.159
The question I'm asking is what does temporal offset afford rather than spatial offset?

00:15:55.039 --> 00:16:05.039
So, this is the example of spatial offset. We could scroll through the different states.

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:11.679
But spatial offset requires us to engage in visual search,

00:16:13.119 --> 00:16:19.280
which requires focused attention and concentration. You've probably experienced this.

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:28.640
But with flip books, you're delivered this blink comparator type experience,

00:16:29.280 --> 00:16:33.840
where you observe different states superimposed and aligned.

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:45.679
And this is a blink comparator. It was used to super align images of the night sky

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:53.280
at different points in time. And it's credited for the discovery of Pluto.

00:16:54.239 --> 00:16:59.840
We found Pluto several decades earlier than we would have otherwise.

00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:09.119
Motion detection makes discovering differences easier.

00:17:12.079 --> 00:17:19.359
To conclude, I would say that flip books has a lot of potential in educational settings.

00:17:19.760 --> 00:17:30.560
But also for reference, you might if you're using a pipeline frequently, but not frequently enough

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:37.439
to recall all of the steps, you might make a flip book out of it and come back to it in the future.

00:17:37.439 --> 00:17:42.880
And also, for communicating what you're doing with colleagues and peers.

00:17:43.040 --> 00:17:51.359
I also think that flip books might be useful in creating greater transparency. Because what API

00:17:51.359 --> 00:17:59.839
we're using shouldn't make people feel like outsiders. It should be clear what's going on,

00:17:59.839 --> 00:18:04.479
no matter what pipeline we're using. So, I want to issue a big thanks to Garek

00:18:04.800 --> 00:18:16.800
and Emi Tanaka for helping get this project off the ground. And I'm also really grateful to a lot

00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:27.359
of critical infrastructures that make the project possible. To testers for their code review. And to

00:18:27.839 --> 00:18:37.040
volunteers. Many of them from Tidy Tuesday, the initiative. To see what would break flip booking.

00:18:38.560 --> 00:18:46.479
And to support at the University of Denver. That's it.

00:18:47.199 --> 00:18:49.599
Thank you.

00:18:49.599 --> 00:19:03.920
So, we have a few questions. And we have a little bit of time. There's the timer.

00:19:04.640 --> 00:19:10.239
So, our first question is, can you use chunk underscore reveal within a markdown document,

00:19:10.239 --> 00:19:15.280
like a blog down page, a markdown report, et cetera, so the flip book works like a GIF

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:16.319
instead of a slideshow?

00:19:19.040 --> 00:19:30.880
So, at this point, no. So, the output that you get is like a full website. So, it's the output

00:19:30.880 --> 00:19:37.119
that sharing gives you, which is the full website. We are looking at different modalities, different

00:19:37.119 --> 00:19:43.280
presentation platforms that we could use. So, one of the things that we're working on is just

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:56.959
delivering a GIF. So, using actually combining images. So, that might be coming up. Yeah.

00:19:57.920 --> 00:20:02.719
And then one more question. When do you expect Flipbooker will be on CRAN?

00:20:06.079 --> 00:20:07.119
May, I guess.

00:20:08.719 --> 00:20:09.520
No promises.

00:20:09.520 --> 00:20:09.920
Thank you.

00:20:11.760 --> 00:20:12.479
Thank you, Gina.

